@0    = ~When I joined you, I swore I would help you as long as you served the greater good. I had hoped you would ammend your ways,  but you have not. This must end. I can no longer be party to such actions.~ [B!GAV_06]
@1    = ~When I joined you, I swore to serve you as long as you worked for the greater good. I have done my part, but your conduct has been less benevolent than I would like. We cannot go on like this! I cannot condone our actions.~ [BGAV_05]
@2    = ~You are leading us well, <CHARNAME>! The gods will smile on our actions. We are surely on the right path.~ [BGAV_02]
@3    = ~<CHARNAME>, I could not be happier about your leadership or about the work that we do. I am proud to call myself a servant of your cause!~ [BGAV_02]
@4    = ~Hello, Blane. How's the back today?~
@5    = ~You'd best be watchin' you don't track mud all over my floors, Gavin.~
@6    = ~What a pity! Let's hope they needed the gold they brought more than the temple.~
@7    = ~Heh. I s'pose. Fine floor, isn't it?~
@8    = ~It's beautiful, Bram.~
@9    = ~Mind you stay away from the gate, lad. Next time old Bram might not be around to let you back out.~
@10   = ~Yes, sir.~
@11   = ~Gods be good, Polus, haven't you dried out yet? Pay him no heed, <CHARNAME>. Just let him go sleep it off.~
@12   = ~Gavin, I know it has been a while since you were our neighbor, but you'll help an old friend, won't you?~
@13   = ~Of course, Mirianne. We'll keep our eyes open and send word if we hear anything.~
@14   = ~Thank you! I know Roe can take care of himself, but I would rest so much easier if I just knew that he is safe.~
@15   = ~And thank you, Gavin, for doing a favor for an old friend.~
@16   = ~I am glad to hear that Roe is in good health and will be on his way home soon. Give him my best when you see him.~
@17   = ~I will. Take care of yourself out there.~
@18   = ~Excuse me for troubling you, then, but is the lady of the house at home?~
@19   = ~No, she is not. I just do odd jobs. If you have business with her, you'll have to return another time. If you write, you might leave a note.~
@20   = ~No, thank you, that will not be necessary... Thank you for your time.~
@21   = ~Well, she must be doing well for herself, if she can have someone come in and do the cleaning.~
@22   = ~Excuse me, <CHARNAME>. I know the... family that lives here now, but they do not appear to be home. If you do not mind, we should go.~
@23   = ~You again?~
@24   = ~Er, yes. You haven't seen them recently, have you?~
@25   = ~Who do you think you are, barging in here and bothering a man who's just trying to earn an honest living?~
@26   = ~The girl is my daughter. I wanted to see her.~
@27   = ~Says you. Or maybe you are the kid's father, if you're the one who's been sending her the money. Anyway, they aren't at home.~
@28   = ~Listen, pal, you seem like a nice enough guy, so I'm going to give you a little advice. When a lady wants to see you, you'll know it. Take the hint, and leave them alone.~
@29   = ~*sigh* Very well.~
@30   = ~We might as well go, <CHARNAME>.~
@31   = ~Davis, it's me, Gavin.~
@32   = ~Oh. Hello, Gavin. Haven't seen you in years. Leave me alone, though. I'm in no mood for talkin'.~
@33   = ~All right, Davis. Sorry to hear things have been so hard for you and yours.~
@34   = ~You should know better, Gavin, bringin' that lot in here. Have you no respect? Get out, the lot of you.~
@35   = ~All right, Davis. I'm sorry. I had no idea things have been so hard for you and yours.~
@36   = ~Hello, Gavin. It's been years. You look well.~
@37   = ~Hello, yourself! Good to see you again, old friend. Is the family keeping well.~
@38   = ~They are, but Darla is visiting her mother with the children, so I have the place to myself for a while. Let us catch up on old times some other time, though. Was there anything you wanted?~
@39   = ~Can that be Gavin, hiding there in the back, with his head down? Don't worry, mate, I've stopped worrying about that bet years ago. So, <SIRMAAM>, where would you like to go?~
@40   = ~Gavin, is that you? I haven't seen your face in ages. I thought you'd died!~
@41   = ~Not yet, Otto, but it has been a while. How's the family?~
@42   = ~Ah, but they're mostly grown, now. The youngest will be wed next month, and then it's me an' the missus, all alone again, just like old times! But listen to me, talkin' when I should be pourin' ale. Can I get you anything, <SIRMAAM>?~
@43   = ~We'll just see about that!~
@44   = ~Gods, what a horrible adversary.~
@45   = ~Did we weather it all right?~
@46   = ~We'll manage.~
@47   = ~I could use some healing.~
@48   = ~<PLAYER2> could use some healing.~
@49   = ~<PLAYER3> could use some healing.~
@50   = ~<PLAYER4> could use some healing.~
@51   = ~<PLAYER5> could use some healing.~
@52   = ~<PLAYER6> could use some healing.~
@53   = ~If you say so...~
@54   = ~Certainly. Let me just see if I have the spell ready...~
@55   = ~Ah, but you are being too forward, to accost weary travelers. Leave us be, man.~
@56   = ~I would oblige, but I am awaiting the friend of a friend. Are you from Candlekeep?~
@57   = ~You've no business asking after names. Leave us be, man.~
@58   = ~I would oblige, but I am awaiting the friend of a friend. Are you <CHARNAME>?~
@59   = ~Now you've asked for it! Time to meet your god!~
@60   = ~This assassin knew much of your business, <CHARNAME>. You've a well-informed enemy.~
@61   = ~Is anyone hurt?~
@62   = ~We're fine. Let's just get inside.~
@63   = ~If you're sure...~
@64   = ~You shouldn't be out here on your own, child.~
@65   = ~You're naught but a bully, lad, and if you've been preying on honest merchants, you deserve the beating I hope you're about to get!~
@66   = ~You say that now, but if you don't hand over your money right quick, you'll see there's power behind that promise!~
@67   = ~<CHARNAME>, you must have heard of Drizzt! How could we not aid him?~
@68   = ~Sounds like a good idea, <CHARNAME>.~
@69   = ~*raises a pale eyebrow* Yes, as I was saying, I must be on my way. Fair journeys to you.~
@70   = ~Child, are you lost, as well?~
@71   = ~I just want my Rufie!~
@72   = ~How can we refuse such a request?~
@73   = ~Just hear me out! It's all I ask!~
@74   = ~<CHARNAME>, you must help them!~
@75   = ~That was close. Good thing you're honest, <CHARNAME>.~
@76   = ~<CHARNAME>, what a dishonest thing to do. We have no right to that gold.~
@77   = ~If you are intent on pursuing this bounty, let us hope that Prism can be persuaded to relinquish the emeralds without resorting to violence. His fate may be of little importance to Oublek, but I would not wish to see him harmed.~
@78   = ~This might have been justice, <CHARNAME>, but it was still wrong. My heart tells me there must have been something else we could have done. But what is done is done. May Brage be shown more kindess in the next life than he was in this.~
@79   = ~I apologize for my companion's rudeness.~
@80   = ~Yes, <CHARNAME>, we must help the people of this town. Tainted ore is bad enough, but we owe it to the families of these miners to do something.~
@81   = ~<CHARNAME>, the lives of the miners and the welfare of this town is at stake. There are more important things than gold.~
@82   = ~For the love of the gods, <CHARNAME>, are you mad?! ~
@83   = ~We will watch for him, ma'am.~
@84   = ~Please accept my condolences, ma'am. I am deeply sorry for your loss.~
@85   = ~<CHARNAME>, you shock me. I could not believe you capable of such cruelty.~
@86   = ~It was the least we could do. May the peace of Lathander bring you comfort.~
@87   = ~Really? Not bad, as cities go, but I prefer the quiet of small towns, myself. What did you see while you were there?~
@88   = ~Buildings and people. People threw stuff at me there, too.~
@89   = ~Poor man.~
@90   = ~Maybe those coins won't be so easily won!~
@91   = ~<CHARNAME>, your foes grow bolder! She was waiting for us here. Waiting! How can we fight an enemy that knows your plans better than you?~
@92   = ~Nice greeting. Who is this guy, anyway?~
@93   = ~Yours is an interesting life, <CHARNAME>. Not many people can boast of being the target of such... confident assassins. Fortunately, his confidence seems to have been misplaced.~
@94   = ~Are you all right?~
@95   = ~Just shaken. I'll recover.~
@96   = ~I'm fine.~
@97   = ~I'm a little dented.~
@98   = ~No thanks to you! I thought you were supposed to protect me from these thugs!~
@99   = ~That is fortunate. This just means that your pursuers haven't given up, so we're going to have to be even more careful.~
@100  = ~Hmmm. You look like you could use a bit of attention, to me. Shall I have a look at your injuries?~
@101  = ~I'll manage on my own. Thanks, anyway.~
@102  = ~If you wouldn't mind.~
@103  = ~Yes, you look like you could use a bit of attention. Shall I have a look at your injuries?~
@104  = ~Like hells you are! Shall I have a look at your injuries?~
@105  = ~I'll say! Just hold still...~
@106  = ~*Ahem* Yes, that was a rather unfortunate lapse. Still, you live yet, so perhaps the gods did not intend you to die this day, with or without my aid.~
@107  = ~If you are certain. I'm at your command, should you change your mind.~
@108  = ~Certainly. Just a moment...~
@109  = ~You are our leader, and I am sworn to see to your physical well-being while I am under your command. I do not need my years of training as a healer to see that you are hurt. Will you let me tend you?~
@110  = ~No, damn it. Stop mothering me!~
@111  = ~Very well.~
@112  = ~<CHARNAME>, you must not let them do this!~
@113  = ~<CHARNAME>, this is wrong!~
@114  = ~Have a care, <CHARNAME>. Hospitality in these parts is a little too convenient for my ease.~
@115  = ~I hope you know what you're doing, <CHARNAME>, because if I understand what he's saying, he's asking us to commit kidnapping and blackmail.~
@116  = ~<CHARNAME>, you are actually going to to go through with this, aren't you? You are in command, but this is wrong.~
@117  = ~We don't know what she's done, <CHARNAME>, but I hate to think what they will do to her if we don't help.~
@118  = ~<CHARNAME>, we must hear him out.~
@119  = ~<CHARNAME>, I, too, thought you were a better person than this. You are our leader, but you disappoint me.~
@120  = ~<CHARNAME>, I cannot advise you in this. I do not want this to become a conflict between two temples, but my heart goes out to Tremain. He should not have to lose his son. I will stand by your decision, however.~
@121  = ~This is hardly an easy question, but I think helping these people is the right thing to do. We should hurry, or the lad will be gone beyond all recall.~
@122  = ~Poor Ragefast. He had no chance. How easy it is to fall in love, to become obsessed with a creature of such bewitching beauty. Yet loveliness and perfection of form are meaningless if the woman they endow is not also possessed of a heart kindred to her would-be lover.~
@123  = ~<CHARNAME>, your kindness has freed them both, although it may be some time before Ragefast realizes it, if he ever does.~
@124  = ~I do not know if Ragefast needed to die for his folly, though in the end, he might well have preferred it to living without the object of his desire.~
@125  = ~<CHARNAME>, how is it that such a beautiful creature can bring out the ugliness in us? We deserve her scorn.~
@126  = ~<CHARNAME>, be careful! Any offer preceeded by a statement like that can hardly be good.~
@127  = ~<CHARNAME>, this man is suggesting we abduct a living creature. Well, someone else has abducted her first, but that is not the point. Agree if you must, but we might consider freeing her from both men, instead.~
@128  = ~*After the briefest moment of shocked silence, Gavin screams and flings himself toward the gnome.*~
@129  = ~Beast! Come here, and I'll strangle you with my own hands! I'll teach you not to hurt children!~
@130  = ~Easy, mate! You're no better, or you wouldn't be in here.~
@131  = ~*still shaking with rage* I will contain my anger for your sake, <CHARNAME>, but I swear by all I hold sacred, if ever I see that gnome again, I will tear him limb from limb.~
@132  = ~*still shaking with rage* Just say the word, <CHARNAME>, and I swear by all I hold sacred, I will tear him limb from limb! Priest or no, I cannot abide the murder of children!~
@133  = ~Get a grip on yourself, man. If you kill me, your hope of escape dies, too. So back off, or your precious <CHARNAME> and the rest of you can rot in here.~
@134  = ~Please, <CHARNAME>, as the father of a small child, I can bear this no longer. If we must play this game again, guess well! My restraint weakens!~
@135  = ~Oh, ho! A small child, he says? Let the mad cleric at me, or guess again. I alone can give you freedom, and only if I live.~
@136  = ~Never that! Gods, get me away from this beast! May a thousand demons haunt your steps from this hour until the end of your miserable life! May you be tormented by every affliction known to man or the gods! May your sleep bring you no rest and waking bring you no relief from your nightmares!~
@137  = ~Be thou at peace, Gavin. The beast hath departed. Let not thy righteous fury overwhelm thee.~
@138  = ~Yes, I can see you are very ill indeed. We will make haste.~
@139  = ~We should help him, <CHARNAME>. Who will protect him if we don't? Nor should such talent be destroyed over a bounty.~
@140  = ~A bad choice, <CHARNAME>. He stole, but he does not deserve to die for it.~
@141  = ~A sad fate, <CHARNAME>, but one we were powerless to avert. Using the potions of haste was unwise, but we can do no more for him. Alas, his work is truly a masterpiece. At least it will endure.~
@142  = ~<CHARNAME>, that was uncalled for. We could have helped him. I am disappointed in you.~
@143  = ~Why did it have to be spiders? Regardless, <CHARNAME>, we must help him.~
@144  = ~<CHARNAME>, you know my feelings about spiders, but I know we must go after this Chelak. I hope for the best, but fear the worst. And when spiders are involved, the worst is pretty bad.~
@145  = ~I am sorry it had to end this way. Please accept my condolences.~
@146  = ~Send those spiders to their deaths! There aren't any arachnophobes here... except for Gavin.~
@147  = ~How adorable. But I admit to a certain bias.~
@148  = ~Dear gods, not again. It was dreadful enough the first time.~
@149  = ~With any luck, Kylee won't need to rely on that dagger for much longer. But let's find him and give it to him anyway, shall we?~
@150  = ~I'm sure he'd like it back.~
@151  = ~Your treachery cost the lives of countless miners and you accuse us?!~
@152  = ~We must stop it! We cannot allow it to go around petrifying everyone!~
@153  = ~This could only be the madman Bassilus.~
@154  = ~I fear High Mornmaster Ormlyr was right. He is clearly insane. But maybe he can still be saved.~
@155  = ~He is indeed beyond hope. We have no choice but to destroy him.~
@156  = ~We have no choice! We must fight for our lives!~
@157  = ~May his god have mercy upon him, he is mad.~
@158  = ~Alas, he is beyond our aid.~
@159  = ~I suppose this could have ended no other way.~
@160  = ~I suppose it was worth a shot.~
@161  = ~How sad it must end this way.~
@162  = ~Sounds like a good idea. What do you say, <CHARNAME>?~
@163  = ~<CHARNAME>, how could you even suggest such a thing!~
@164  = ~Why is it that someone can do something as incredibly evil as wiping out an entire clan of dwarves or enslaving scores of miners, and then wonder why we want to talk to him? Talk to the hammer, fiend!~
@165  = ~Come, then, <CHARNAME>, we owe Duke Eltan our aid. Let us see what we can do for him.~
@166  = ~Do not let this unsettle you, <CHARNAME>. The future is uncertain, true, but we have a hand in our own destiny.~
@167  = ~<CHARNAME>, how greedy can you be? The woman has been stone for the gods know how long, and you would take all she has?~
@168  = ~A charitable deed.~
@169  = ~Poor kid. He didn't stand a chance.~
@170  = ~*gulp* And what a horrible way to go.~
@171  = ~My gods, <CHARNAME>,... this place... I feel faint!~
@172  = ~You can do this, Gavin. Just keep it together a little while, and you'll be all right.~
@173  = ~Suck it up, man!~
@174  = ~Oh, for gods' sakes, Gavin, not now!~
@175  = ~Thanks. I'll try not to let you down.~
@176  = ~Trying, <SIRMAAM>.~
@177  = ~Do you think I want to be like this?!~
@178  = ~Poor blighter. The halfling almost made it back to Beregost with the letter.~
@179  = ~Well, this is good news! Travelling in winter is unpleasant, but at least he is safe and well. We should tell Mirianne as soon as possible.~
@180  = ~Yes, this was the place. I lived here for five years, but it seems a lifetime ago.~
@181  = ~I do not recognize this man, but that is hardly surprising.~
@182  = ~<CHARNAME>, can we please leave immediately. This is the home of Greta, a former neighbor I have no wish to meet again. She's indisposed, it seems. We are incredibly lucky. Let's not push our luck by lingering.~
@183  = ~Greta, eh? An old flame?~
@184  = ~Why do you dislike her?~
@185  = ~Whatever.~
@186  = ~No, Gavin. Let's check for valuables. No reason not to, if you don't like her, anyway.~
@187  = ~Gods, no! Just an irritable, petty woman with an ear for gossip.~
@188  = ~She's just an irritable, petty woman with an ear for gossip, nothing more. But that does not mean that I wish to run into her.~
@189  = ~Then let's leave quickly, shall we?~
@190  = ~Just because I don't like her is no reason to rob her. I have no taste for burglary. Let's leave, shall we?~
@191  = ~Yeuck! Please, I beg you, <CHARNAME>, do not ask me to carry that thing! I cannot abide spiders.~
@192  = ~YIIEEE! <CHARNAME>, please, have mercy on me! Give it to anyone else!~
@193  = ~My word! I... do not think that was a normal child!~
@194  = ~Another grieving family! I fear this will never end until the bandits are destroyed.~
@195  = ~Damn! How I wished we could bring the poor man's widow happier news! As if she did not have cares enough.~
@196  = ~Oh, very funny. Although I should be thankful for the opportunity to experience life as a woman, I am having a difficult time reconciling my sense of identity with my new body. Next time we're in town, can we get this removed?~
@197  = ~A tremendous improvement, if you ask me. (Although, I note that no one has. No matter. They are clearly deficient in wisdom, or they would have me leading the party instead of that fool <CHARNAME>.)~
@198  = ~Where did Gavin go?~
@199  = ~Tee, hee! Ya look good as a girl, Gavin. Too bad about that nose, though.~
@200  = ~If you are done playing, children, we have work to do.~
@201  = ~I'm a man again! Thank the gods! Lathander bless you, <CHARNAME>, I was not put on Toril to be a woman. The obsession about my complexion was bad enough, but the bloating was impossible!~
@202  = ~So now what?~
@203  = ~Jump~
@204  = ~Go back down, I guess.~
@205  = ~Like hells! We go down the stairs like normal people, or as close as we can manage. I have no fear of death, but I don't want to go this soon!~
@206  = ~Only choice, I guess. I am looking forward to going home to Lathander, but I would rather it wasn't today.~
@207  = ~That letter... says your father is Bhaal, the god of murder.~
@208  = ~And...~
@209  = ~That's what it says, but I am having trouble believing it. You would have thought there would have been some hint before now!~
@210  = ~Do you fear me because of it?~
@211  = ~And just think of all the possibilities.~
@212  = ~*And*?! And this is a little more serious than inheriting your father's nose or your mother's aptitude for music!~
@213  = ~You have the blood of a god in your veins, and not a benevolent god at that.~
@214  = ~What are you trying to tell me?~
@215  = ~I didn't ask for this, you know!~
@216  = ~I'm trying to tell you that you're going to have to make a big decision here. It all depends on you. Are you going to give in to the taint?~
@217  = ~I don't see it as a taint. I see it as an opportunity. All the possibilities...~
@218  = ~No! I will fight it, and keep doing what I know is right!~
@219  = ~All the possibilities? If you take that attitude, the only possibility this is going to give you is to become a monster. Is that what you want?~
@220  = ~No. I will fight it.~
@221  = ~If that is what it takes to gain that kind of power, I welcome it!~
@222  = ~Then I will gladly help you.~
@223  = ~Then it is time for us to part company. I am sorry.~
@224  = ~Oh, I know you did not. Who would? But the question is, now that you know what you are, what are you going to do with the knowledge?~
@225  = ~I just don't know, Gavin.~
@226  = ~I am still thinking about all the possibilities.~
@227  = ~Whatever else, I am not going to become evil. I will do what I have to do to fight whatever taint I have inherited.~
@228  = ~I hope you decide soon. You are not going to have long to make up your mind.~
@229  = ~What do you think the last several months have been? I know you have no control over who your father was. But the question is, now that you know what you are, what are you going to do with the knowledge?~
@230  = ~No, but I fear what you might become. I know you have no control over who your father was. But the question is, now that you know what you are, what are you going to do with the knowledge?~
@231  = ~The price on your head must really be substantial, to merit such persistance. We're just going to have to work that much harder to keep you safe.~
@232  = ~Xan, I have to talk to you.~
@233  = ~(sigh) Yes, you've been giving me strange looks for the past few hours. Not without reason, I suspect?~
@234  = ~No doubt. Xan, about <CHARNAME>, how could you?~
@235  = ~How, Gavin? Or why?~
@236  = ~I do not want to believe you capable of this! You, of all people! You led her to believe that you cared for her! She trusted you! Why? Why have you done this?~
@237  = ~Gavin, do you know what true closeness is?~
@238  = ~I know what it should be. Two people have similar beliefs, like valuing duty or showing mercy, share the same goals. A day without the other is a day lost. I is *not* about abandoning those who trust in you, and who... love you.~
@239  = ~It is indeed. And then what?~
@240  = ~I do not understand you.~
@241  = ~No, you don't. Few non-elves do. Gavin, when two humans grow closer the way you describe, they are generally happy. They lie together, they share their secrets... sometimes they marry and rear children.~
@242  = ~What would you know of human love? It is not so cold.~
@243  = ~Gavin, when elves love, there is more. We are a part of the Spirit, and we communicate within it... we are dead without it. And it is all too hard not to be of one heart with the one I love.~
@244  = ~There is much more to love than this. What of the simple joy of beholding the one you love, and knowing that they are happy? Or the giddy delight if that happiness is at least partially because her world contains you? Or the comfort of knowing that another soul knows everything there is to know about you, and loves you anyway?~
@245  = ~Perhaps. I thought so, once. But the lack of the oneness within the Weave only brings more and more pain. And eventually, only the lesser of the two evils remains.~
@246  = ~There is also the quiet contentment of emotional and physical togetherness, and the certainty that the years bring you nothing but memories of the life and the love you have shared. You should not have given up so quickly.~
@247  = ~Togetherness? Have you heard nothing? There is no true togetherness outside of the Spirit. No sharing of emotions; memories, falling apart. There is only pain.~
@248  = ~And what of her pain, Xan? You rejected her for something she could not even control!~
@249  = ~And would her pain have been less years hence, when the emptiness became unbearable?~
@250  = ~Many other elves have decided differently. And who could say they were not happy?~
@251  = ~I do not know, Gavin. I only know about myself, and that I am too weak to take this.~
@252  = ~Still, I think that you should at least ask her for forgiveness. Do you even know what she must be feeling now?~
@253  = ~Much the same as I, I suspect. But I shall not say more. And, no, I do not think I will approach her - and certainly not any other, elf or no - again.~
@254  = ~<CHARNAME> is the best leader ever, but sometimes <PRO_HESHE> hurts me. I miss my family. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@255  = ~<CHARNAME> is the best leader ever, but I miss my family. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@256  = ~Sometimes, <CHARNAME> hurts me. I miss my family. I wish it did not have to be this way. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@257  = ~I miss my family. I wish it did not have to be this way. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@258  = ~I am in love with <CHARNAME>, but sometimes she hurts me. I want her to love me, but I need to be careful. I miss my family. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@259  = ~I am in love with <CHARNAME>. I want her to love me. I miss my family. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@260  = ~I like <CHARNAME>, but sometimes she hurts me. I miss my family. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@261  = ~I like <CHARNAME>, but I miss my family. I hope Lanie is all right.~
@262  = ~I love <CHARNAME> with all my heart. She hurts me sometimes, but I would be lost without her. I miss Lanie. I want her to live with <CHARNAME> and I.~
@263  = ~I love <CHARNAME> with all my heart. I would be lost without her. I miss Lanie. I want her to live with <CHARNAME> and I.~
@264  = ~I love <CHARNAME> with all my heart, but I don't know if she loves me as much as I love her. She hurts me sometimes, but I would be lost without her. I miss Lanie. I want her to live with <CHARNAME> and I.~
@265  = ~I love <CHARNAME> with all my heart, but I don't know if she loves me as much as I love her. I would be lost without her. I miss Lanie. I want her to live with <CHARNAME> and I.~
@266  = ~I dislike <CHARNAME> intensely, but I need the money to send to Lanie. I hope she is all right. I miss my family.~
@267  = ~I am only doing this because I need the money to send to Lanie. I hope she is all right. I miss my family.~
