@544  = ~I don't know if this is really any of your business.~
@545  = ~I am sorry to hear that. Please accept my deepest condolences for your loss. Forgive me if I sound like I am prying, but I cannot help but wonder why anyone would wish such a man dead. Not that I have heard much about him at the temple, but what I have heard has been entirely favorable.~
@546  = ~You did not have to live with him! If you did, I am sure you would be able to think of plenty of reasons to kill him.~
@547  = ~I don't know why they killed him. It was not as if he needed many enemies. Just one.~
@548  = ~A powerful mage like Gorion is bound to have made a few enemies over the years.~
@549  = ~Thanks for the sympathy, but it really is too soon to talk about it.~
@550  = ~Thanks for the sympathy, but I am not even sure that Gorion was their target. They might have been after me.~
@551  = ~Whatever. Just get back to doing whatever it is clerics do.~
@552  = ~You're prying.~
@553  = ~Yet here you are, pursuing his murderers. You must have had some affection for him to abandon the safety of your home to chase after them.~
@554  = ~Not a bit. But if they were powerful enough to take out Gorion, they must be worth something.~
@555  = ~Yes, I do. It's just that this is has all happened so fast, I haven't really learned to accept his loss. So I say odd things, sometimes.~
@556  = ~My, this is awkward. I cannot say I endorse your search, under those conditions, but I hope that after the initial shock has worn off, you will consider more altruistic pursuits.~
@557  = ~Ah, I understand completely. And I apologize for my insensitivity. It must be very hard for you. I'll support you any way I can.~
@558  = ~That is true, but it does mean that it is going to be difficult to find him, especially without any leads. I'll help you, of course, but I was wondering how your search for your foster father's murderer related to your current activities. Did he have anything to do with bandit activities or the iron shortage?~
@559  = ~Certainly not that I'm aware of, but doing something is better than doing nothing. The chance is remote, but maybe it is somehow connected.~
@560  = ~Gorion did keep some influential company. It is always possible that someone of his association had an interest in current events and wanted to prevent his interference.~
@561  = ~Probably not, but it beats sitting at home in Candlekeep wishing I knew what was going on.~
@562  = ~I don't want to talk about this anymore.~
@563  = ~I suppose that's something. If nothing else, I admire your goals. A lot of people *would* sit at home and wait for the authorities to figure it out. Even if you don't find his killer, at least you will have made some good come of it.~
@564  = ~That is always possible, but if you are right, it could mean that we are up against a powerful enemy, indeed. You have my support, of course, but we'll have to be careful.~
@565  = ~As you wish. I apologize if I have been too nosy for your comfort.~
@566  = ~It's always possible, of course. But that opens the possibility that Gorion's unknown enemy or enemies could be involved with current events. If so, we might very well encounter them. We will have to be cautious.~
@567  = ~Whatever. Look, Gavin, if this trip is too dangerous for you, you can always go home.~
@568  = ~You are right, on both counts. I do not think we should stop what we're doing because it might be dangerous, but I think we should be careful.~
@569  = ~Maybe you are right about the powerful enemies, but I'm not going to give up if just because it might be dangerous.~
@570  = ~No, I'm not worried about my own neck... well, all right, I am, but I'm not about to let that stop me from helping you. Come on. Let's do what we can, and be careful.~
@571  = ~Then we stand a chance. Come on. Let's do what we can.~
@572  = ~No, I'm not saying that you should. I'm just saying that you should be careful. Hey, it isn't only my own neck I'm worried about here. There are a lot of good people who could be hurt if we go charging off and do something stupid. So let's move forwawrd, but carefully.~
@573  = ~Then I apologize. I had no intention of making you uncomfortable.~
@574  = ~That's horrible! What makes you say that?~
@575  = ~"Surrender your ward and nobody gets hurt" sounds pretty unambiguous to me.~
@576  = ~Just a hunch.~
@577  = ~Maybe I was mistaken.~
@578  = ~Yes, it is hard to take that any other way. I will help you, of course, but we will have to be exceptionally careful. Anyone powerful enough to take out a mage like Gorion is going to be a tough opponent.~
@579  = ~Ah. Well, in the absence of any conclusive proof, it is probably best to assume the worst, that it *was* you they were after. I'll help you, of course, but we'll need to be very careful.~
@580  = ~I hope so, but it would be wise to be careful, in any event.~
@581  = ~Sorry, I was just trying to help. Would you rather I kept quiet for the rest of the trip?~
@582  = ~No. I'm sorry. It's just too soon, and I'm having a hard time being polite to anyone, these days.~
@583  = ~Yes.~
@584  = ~No, it's all right. I understand that this is a very difficult time for you.~
@585  = ~I suppose this is a good an opportunity as any. But you seem to be driven by more than just dissatisfaction of the enforced quiet of small-town life. Is there another reason for this trip?~
@586  = ~No.~
@587  = ~My foster father, Gorion was murdered. I am looking for his killers.~
@588  = ~Well, if you are looking for excitement, you will probably find it in abundance.~
@589  = ~That is admirable, and I feel the same way. But, if I might be so inquisitive, why here and now?~
@590  = ~My foster father, Gorion was murdered. I want to do my part to improve the Sword Coast, but I am also looking for his killers.~
@591  = ~The area seems to be in need of some help, but I must confess that I always found Candlekeep to be too restrictive. It's a small town, without much to do. I am looking for adventure, as much as anything else.~
@592  = ~I feel that I should do something for the people of this area. The iron crisis and the bandits have left it very vulnerable. I want to help.~
@593  = ~I can hardly argue with that.~
@594  = ~I get the feeling that you do not want to talk about this.~
@595  = ~No, I do. You see, my foster father, Gorion was murdered. I want to do my part to improve the Sword Coast, but I am also looking for his killers.~
@596  = ~Well, I admit that the area seems to be in need of some help, but I always found Candlekeep to be too restrictive. It's a small town, without much to do. I am looking for adventure, as much as anything else.~
@597  = ~Not really.~
@598  = ~Sorry, I did not mean to offend. Would you rather I kept quiet for the rest of the trip?~
@599  = ~No. I'm sorry. I've just got a lot on my mind, and I'm having a hard time being polite to anyone, these days.~
@600  = ~No, it's all right. I have a tendency to babble, sometimes.~
@601  = ~<CHARNAME>, do you serve a god?~
@602  = ~Like you, I serve Lathander.~
@603  = ~I serve Helm.~
@604  = ~I do, but I do not serve Lathander.~
@605  = ~I worship Chauntea, goddess of things that grow.~
@606  = ~I worship Gond, god of smiths and artisans.~
@607  = ~I worship Helm, god of vigilance.~
@608  = ~I worship Ilmater, god of martyrdom and perseverance.~
@609  = ~I worship Kelemvor, god of the dead.~
@610  = ~I worship Lathander, too.~
@611  = ~I worship Lliira, goddess of joy.~
@612  = ~I worship Mielikki, goddess of the forests.~
@613  = ~I worship Mystra, goddess of magic.~
@614  = ~I worship Oghma, god of knowledge.~
@615  = ~I worship Selune, goddess of the moon.~
@616  = ~I worship Sharess, goddess of sensual pleasure.~
@617  = ~I worship Silvanus, god of nature.~
@618  = ~I worship Sune, goddess of love and beauty.~
@619  = ~I worship Tempus, god of battle.~
@620  = ~I worship Tymora, goddess of fortune.~
@621  = ~I worship Tyr, god of justice.~
@622  = ~I worship Umberlee, goddess of the sea.~
@623  = ~I worship Berronar Truesilver, goddess of family and obligations.~
@624  = ~I worship Clangeddin Silverbeard, god of battle and honor.~
@625  = ~I worship Dugmaren Brightmantle, god of invention.~
@626  = ~I worship Dumathoin, god of metal and burried wealth.~
@627  = ~I worship Gorm Gulthyn, protector of the dwarves.~
@628  = ~I worship Moradin, creation and smithing.~
@629  = ~I worship Sharindlar, god of healing.~
@630  = ~I worship Vergadain, god of luck.~
@631  = ~I revere all the Morndinsamman.~
@632  = ~I worship Corellon Larethian, god of elven magic and the arts.~
@633  = ~I worship Hanali Celanil, goddess of love.~
@634  = ~I worship Rillifane Rallathil, god of the woodlands.~
@635  = ~I revere all the Seladarine.~
@636  = ~I worship Baervan Wildwanderer, god of nature.~
@637  = ~I worship Baravar Cloakshadow, god of illusion.~
@638  = ~I worship Flandal Steelskin, god of mining and smithing.~
@639  = ~I worship Garl Glittergold, god of the Gnomes.~
@640  = ~I revere all the Lords of the Golden Hills.~
@641  = ~I worship Arvoreen, god of warriors.~
@642  = ~I worship Brandobaris, god of rogues.~
@643  = ~I worship Cyrrollalee, goddess of the home.~
@644  = ~I worship Sheela Peryroyl, goddess of nature, love and beauty.~
@645  = ~I worship Yondalla, goddess of the halflings.~
@646  = ~I revere all of Yondallas Children.~
@647  = ~I worship a different god.~
@648  = ~I revere all the gods.~
@649  = ~I am indifferent toward religion.~
@650  = ~I serve no god.~
@651  = ~It's good to have a <PRO_BROTHERSISTER> in faith. My family gave nodding respect to all the gods, but my mother always had a special reverence for Lathander, as well.~
@652  = ~I was to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same for you?~
@653  = ~Yes, it was.~
@654  = ~Not really. I discovered my faith when I was nearly grown.~
@655  = ~Actually, faith isn't important to me at all. I mostly go my own way.~
@656  = ~That's good to know.~
@657  = ~Better later than never.~
@658  = ~I suppose there is room for that, too. Maybe you just haven't found the right religion, though. Don't worry. I'm no missionary.~
@659  = ~Helm's teachings and Lathander's are sometimes at odds, but I see no reason why that should be a problem in this group. There is certainly no reason the followers of any benevolent deities can not cooperate.~
@660  = ~I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same for you?~
@661  = ~Still you are a <PRO_MANWOMAN> of faith. And it is good to be travelling in the company of a servant of a benevolent deity.~
@662  = ~I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@663  = ~*smiles* My sister Della worships Chauntea, well mostly Chauntea. She is an avid gardener, though, so it makes sense.~
@664  = ~I, myself, was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@665  = ~*smiles faintly* A genius of a god, I must say, and creative in a very physical way. The faith is not at odds with the teachings of Lathander, who values creativity in any form, but I lack the mechanical aptitude to grasp the details.~
@666  = ~I, on the other hand, felt drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@667  = ~*smiles faintly* A stern god, but the fairness of his followers is enviable, especially when things are uneasy. I understand why the order of the religion is appealing, but I could never handle the routine. My father is a follwer of Tyr.~
@668  = ~*smiles sadly* I suppose all turn their prayers to Ilmater at times. One always has recourse with the god of perseverance and mercy, but there never seems to be an end to suffering in this life. Followers of Ilmater must be very special.~
@669  = ~While I certainly respect Ilmater, I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@670  = ~*smiles sadly* I suppose all must know about him, in the end, and he is fair, if not overly merciful. Forgive me, but I don't really understand his worship. As a healer, I understand the necessity, but there is very little joy there.~
@671  = ~I have been drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@672  = ~You must have had a very unusual childhood.~
@673  = ~I find that vaguely reassuring.~
@674  = ~*smiles* How delightful. The world certainly needs more of her followers. They must be very special people.~
@675  = ~*smiles* Then there is a kinship between our faiths. Clerics of Lathander are taught to revere things that grow, although I can not say we approach it with the same zeal as the follower of a forest deity would. I, myself, have never had any luck with plants, though it shames me to admit it.~
@676  = ~Even so, I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@677  = ~Ah. Well, that makes sense, given your profession.~
@678  = ~The god of knowledge and learning? A worthwhile religion, certainly. As a matter of fact, my sister Reed pays special devotion to him. But she's a scholar and a mage, so it's only natural. But my, she has a sense of humor. She inherited this ring I wear from a great uncle, who was also a mage. She knew I liked it, so she gave it to me as a present when I was ordained. Thing was, she placed an enchantment on it so now it won't come off! Not that I really want to take it off, anyway. I think of her little joke every time I look at it, and it always makes me smile.~
@679  = ~But back to religion. I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@680  = ~Selune and Lathander are allies, and our faiths are complimentary, on a basic level. You worship moonlight, I, sunlight, but they are both part of the natural cycle. And followers of Selune are no less devoted enemies of evil than Lathandrites.~
@681  = ~*Gavin looks inexplicably uncomfortable.* Ah. I see. Well...~
@682  = ~About Lathander, I mean my service to Lathander, I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith? No, don't answer that! Please forgive me. What a dreadful question!~
@683  = ~*smile* as a matter of fact, it was.~
@684  = ~Not surprisingly, I discovered my faith when I was nearly grown.~
@685  = ~Oh, my! If you'll excuse me, I think I need to check to make sure my pack is closed. I'll catch up.~
@686  = ~Ah, well, that's a relief. If you'll excuse me, I think I need to check to make sure my pack is closed. I'll catch up.~
@687  = ~I see. If you'll excuse me, I think I need to check to make sure my pack is closed. I'll catch up.~
@688  = ~Ah, yes. I can't say I've had much opportunity to watch his followers in action. Most of my time in that arena has been spent cleaning up the aftermath. Still, everything has a purpose.~
@689  = ~Ah, well that's convenient. You will put in a good word for us, I hope?~
@690  = ~You actually chose that... capricious goddess as your patron? I suppose people where I grew up gave her tribute, but I can't say she was worshipped as much as feared. That is her nature. The whole region did depend upon the sea, so it was only natural. Not the kindest of deities, but the sea is not always gentle.~
@691  = ~*smile* Well, religion is all about what is important, and it is hard to imagine anything more important than the home and family.~
@692  = ~*smile* I cannot say I am all that knowledgeable where Dumathoin is concerned, but that is probalby the point. He is also the god of secret knowledge, isn't he?~
@693  = ~*smile* The patron and protector of your people. You must enjoy the sense of community conveyed through your worship. Lathander advocates harmony between all the races, but maybe finding a shared purpose within the community is a good first step.~
@694  = ~*smile* A kindred spirit in a way. I've always found that aspect of my work to be the most rewarding.~
@695  = ~First among the Seldarine. You must enjoy the sense of community conveyed through your worship. Lathander advocates harmony between all the races, but maybe finding a shared purpose within the community is a good first step.~
@696  = ~Who will come to claim you in the afterlife, then? But everyone must walk their own road, I guess.~
@697  = ~I felt drawn to Lathander from an early age. Have you always felt the way you do, or was this more recent?~
@698  = ~I have always had a more general approach to religion.~
@699  = ~Not really. I underwent a recent crisis of faith.~
@700  = ~Well, there is always hope. Maybe you have not yet felt a kinship to any particular faith.~
@701  = ~Well, there is always hope. I hope you are able to reconcile your crisis soon.~
@702  = ~That is risky, with the afterlife that uncertain. Who knows who will claim you with no patron? But I would never tell anyone how to live.~
@703  = ~Worship of any benevolent god can really give you a sense of purpose, don't you think? I was drawn to Lathander from an early age. Was it the same with your faith?~
@704  = ~That's risky. Who will claim you in the afterlife? I, myself, felt drawn to Lathander from an early age. Maybe you just haven't found the right faith?~
@705  = ~No, I just don't like clerics.~
@706  = ~No, I just resent people telling me how to live my life.~
@707  = ~Maybe, but I have no desire to look.~
@708  = ~Maybe you can tell me about Lathander sometime. Maybe later, though.~
@709  = ~Sorry if I offended you.~
@710  = ~Not all religions do. Lathander, for example, asks very little of his followers. But I have taken much of your time. Maybe another day.~
@711  = ~You don't have to look. You will know it when you see it. But I have taken much of your time. I'll leave you be for a while.~
@712  = ~I would love to, but I think I have taken enough of your time for a while. Later, perhaps.~
@713  = ~Making a wild guess, I suppose you don't like talking about religion, either. Fair enough.~
@714  = ~May I ask your opinion on something, <CHARNAME>?~
@715  = ~Please do.~
@716  = ~Not now, Gavin.~
@717  = ~No, Gavin. Not now, not ever.~
@718  = ~As you wish. I shall walk elsewhere.~
@719  = ~Maybe later, then.~
@720  = ~One of the goals of Lathander's clergy is to promote interracial harmony. I think this is a noble and worthwhile goal, but sometimes, I wonder if cooperation between all peoples is possible. I wondered if you think this is possible, or even desirable.~
@721  = ~It might be possible, but I do not think it is desirable.~
@722  = ~I agree with you when you say that it is desirable, but I do not think it is possible.~
@723  = ~I believe that is neither.~
@724  = ~I think that it is both possible and desirable.~
@725  = ~Ugh. I do *not* want to talk about this.~
@726  = ~How about sentient spiders? Should we try to cooperate with them?~
@727  = ~You've got me there. I do not think I will ever be able to overcome my fear to that extent. Braver people might, though.~
@728  = ~Very well. I'll drop the subject. It is rather heavy for this time of the <DAYNIGHT>.~
@729  = ~That's a reassuring thought. If you wouldn't mind talking a little bit more about it, though, I'd also like to know why you feel as you do.~
@730  = ~I am not really in the mood to explain it.~
@731  = ~I can't see why everyone does *not* want it. Seriously, though, all it would take is a little encouragement, and a strong enough deterrent for people who stir up trouble.~
@732  = ~The benefits of such cooperation would be many. Peace, improved understanding, and improved trade are just some of the more obvious ones. I think mutual communication is a necessary first step. That leads to eventual understanding, which leads to tolerance, which leads to acceptance and harmony.~
@733  = ~I don't think there is an easy answer.~
@734  = ~If I think about it any longer, my head might explode.~
@735  = ~Fair enough. Thank you for your opinion.~
@736  = ~That sounds strangely ominous. What do you mean by encouragement, and what do you mean by deterrent?~
@737  = ~You'd think it would be obvious.~
@738  = ~By encouragement, I mean people should be made to do as they are told, and by deterrent, I mean that penalties for doing otherwise should be severe enough to prevent a recurrence, if you know what I mean.~
@739  = ~People are encouraged when they can see the positive results of their actions on a personal level. I know you can't control the thoughts of another, but you can influence their actions. A reward for behavior that fosters goodwill would help them realize the value of cooperation. A stiff fine, I think, would be enough of a deterrent for most people to avoid a second offense.~
@740  = ~I don't know, really. I like the idea, and think it could work, but I don't know if I'm qualified to think up an implementation strategy.~
@741  = ~I'm getting a headache, thinking about this.~
@742  = ~Not really, but I don't know if I want to hear the explanation after all. I apologize for starting a conversation and not finishing it, but I have a feeling we are not going to agree about the whys and wherefores, and I have no desire to stir friction in the group.~
@743  = ~It sounds more like domination of the weak by the strong to me. The very concept is against everything Lathander stands for. I am deeply troubled by your answer, and wish I had not asked.~
@744  = ~If that's what you want to call it, then yes, that would be preferable to pandering to everyone that wants to be 'special.'~
@745  = ~No, that came out wrong. I didn't mean it quite that way.~
@746  = ~I cannot believe you said that, and in my presence. That might compell compliance, but it is most definitely *not* a way to foster harmony.~
@747  = ~No matter how you meant it, it was still offensive.~
@748  = ~Appealing to a person's greed does not sound like the best of all possible worlds, but at least it isn't overly oppressive.~
@749  = ~Fair enough. That's always the stumbling block I hit. I want it, and I think it could work, but I have no idea how.~
@750  = ~Ha! I know the feeling. That's what happens when I think about it too long.~
@751  = ~A long, slow road, but one that might end well. That is probably the only long term solution, but it takes time, and progress is hard to measure. If you're a dreamer, then we both are.~
@752  = ~And *that* is precisely the problem.~
@753  = ~Ha! I know the feeling.~
@754  = ~I am inclined to disagree, but I would like to hear why you feel that way.~
@755  = ~You will never get people of different races to get along. They are just too different. After that, it makes no sense to even think about whether or not it is desirable.~
@756  = ~You would be asking people to give up their identity. No one is going to go along with that, nor should they.~
@757  = ~That is where we disagree. I do not think people are all that different. We all need the same things: food, shelter, warmth, love. Tastes may differ about what best satisfies those needs, but where there is common ground, there can be understanding.~
@758  = ~When one race's idea of food includes you, that limits the opportunity to further understanding.~
@759  = ~I don't think I want to talk about this, after all.~
@760  = ~I can see where that would be a problem. How depressing.~
@761  = ~I can see this conversation is going nowhere. Thanks for your time.~
@762  = ~Fair enough. Thank you for your time.~
@763  = ~I disagree. People do not have to give up their identities, they just have to learn that their identity does not give them the right to judge anyone who does not share it. But I can see that if we keep talking like this, I am going to wind up offending you, and I don't want that.~
@764  = ~So perhaps we will have to agree to disagree.~
@765  = ~I am afraid that you might be right, but it would be wrong for me to lose faith so easily. Why do *you* think it might not be possible?~
@766  = ~It is hard enough getting one person to abandon long-held prejudices. Just imagine that on a racial scale.~
@767  = ~People have this need to feel superior. Cooperation implies equality. That concept will never be universally popular.~
@768  = ~People like to fight. People on a racial scale like war. You are as unlikely to see racial cooperation as you are to see a world without war.~
@769  = ~That is my fear as well. *sigh* Well, there is no reason to give up on a dream even if the chance of success is slim. I'll keep hoping, but try not to be disappointed if I don't live to see it.~
@770  = ~Maybe not, but I can still hope.~
@771  = ~That is a very bleak picture. I sincerely hope you are wrong.~
@772  = ~Who would get to decide what is right? Peole would never stop squabbling.~
@773  = ~Because I shudder to think of what that would do to racial purity. First people start cooperating, then they start liking each other, and next thing you know, we've got a world full of mongrels. Let each race keep to themselves.~
@774  = ~There would be the risk of losing cultural identity.~
@775  = ~I would like to think that part of cooperation would mean working together to resolve things instead of forcing right/wrong decisions, but I might be a dreamer.~
@776  = ~Endangering racial purity? Mongrels? Surely you did not mean to phrase that so offensively.~
@777  = ~Yes, actually I did. I happen to like the idea of racial purity, and I don't really want to see a lot of half <PRO_RACE> children running around.~
@778  = ~No, I did not mean it the way it sounded. I just think people need to maintain their cultural identity.~
@779  = ~No, I did not mean it that way at all! I do not know what made me say that.~
@780  = ~That is really quite offensive. I think we should drop this subject immediately.~
@781  = ~I do not think that would necessarily follow. Elves will not stop being elves if they learn to cooperate with dwarves, for example. But I think we have talked about this long enough. This conversation is a little too inflamatory for my taste.~
@782  = ~That's all right. Things slip out sometimes. But that is part of the reason why everyone would benefit from such cooperation.~
@783  = ~<CHARNAME>, will you look at this! I could have sworn I packed these herbs correctly.~
@784  = ~They don't look too good, do they? I would have thought a cleric might be more adept with herbs.~
@785  = ~Is it supposed to be that... color?~
@786  = ~On the bright side, I think you now have a fine fungus collection.~
@787  = ~Can't you do anything right?~
@788  = ~So would I. I swear on Lathander's golden pinky toe, I am truly hopeless when it comes to plants. And herbs are supposed to thrive on neglect. I grew these herbs, harvested them, and thought I had dried them properly, now this!~
@789  = ~Maybe they're supposed to be brownish black when they dry. Were they fuzzy when you harvested them?~
@790  = ~Looks like you packed them wet. Or you got them wet at some point after they were dried. We have been out of doors a lot.~
@791  = ~I doubt I would have been able to do much better. Have you ever grown and dried herbs before?~
@792  = ~No. The ones I bought before I tried my hand at horticulture were kind of a light greenish-brown and rather crispy. Not these leathery black things. It is my secret shame. Lathander is supposed to favor those that foster plant growth, but I must have escaped his notice. I can do all the heavy garden work there is, right up to the point where the plants sprout. I have never had a way with plants. Brewing them, now, is a different story.~
@793  = ~It doesn't matter, I suppose. I can buy more once we're in town. But I would consider it a personal favor if you promised not to develop any scaly skin afflictions until then.~
@794  = ~Maybe, but I could have sworn they were dry enough. Apparently, I was mistaken. I do not think they could have gotten wet in my pack. I had it packed in oilcloth, and everything else is nice and dry.~
@795  = ~Lathander is supposed to favor those that foster plant growth, but I must have escaped his notice. I can do all the heavy garden work there is, right up to the point where the plants sprout. I have never had a way with plants. Brewing them, now, is a different story.~
@796  = ~No, I've usually either used the supply at the temple or purchased them in town.~
@797  = ~Good point. I wonder what it's good for, though. Maybe it would be safer just to throw it out.~
@798  = ~Ouch. I had no idea I was *that* inept.~
@799  = ~I'm sorry Gavin. I was making a joke, but I guess it was a bad one. I will admit that you will never make a good herbalist, but you are no more incompetent than the next person.~
@800  = ~You take yourself too seriously, Gavin. I was making a joke.~
@801  = ~Frankly, I'm surprised you haven't managed to kill yourself with your own hammer.~
@802  = ~No, I probably shouldn't take myself so seriously. But, clumsy as I am, I'm a bit self-conscious.~
@803  = ~*sheepish smile* I suppose you're right. But, clumsy as I am, I'm a bit self-conscious.~
@804  = ~You aren't winning any points, here. I do my best. If you want me to leave, just give the orders.~
@805  = ~<CHARNAME>, have you given any thought to what you will do when your quest is over?~
@806  = ~No, not really. It seems too far away to plan.~
@807  = ~I might try to resume a quiet life, whether at Candlekeep or somewhere else.~
@808  = ~Now that I've gotten a taste for adventuring, I don't see myself doing anything else.~
@809  = ~I don't see how this could be your business.~
@810  = ~Fair enough. But one day, this quest will end, and you will need to think about it eventually. You seem to have developed a flair for adventuring. Do you think you might like to go on?~
@811  = ~I might. Are you offering your services?~
@812  = ~I might, but if I do, I don't think I'll need a cleric, if you know what I mean.~
@813  = ~No, I think I'd like to settle down. I'm getting tired of the uncertainty.~
@814  = ~I really have no idea. I'll make that decision when the time comes.~
@815  = ~I might be tempted, but I have some family business to take care of first.~
@816  = ~I'm sorry your experience travelling with a cleric has been such a disappointment, then. But no hard feelings. I need to address some family business after this quest, anyway.~
@817  = ~I can certainly understand that. I'd like to settle down myself, but I don't think I'll have the opportunity for a while. I have some family business to conclude after this quest, and even after that is done, I think I will still have some travelling to do before I can settle anywhere for long.~
@818  = ~I can certainly understand that. Everything is so uncertain. I'd like to settle down myself, but I don't think I'll have the opportunity for a while. I have some family business to conclude after this quest, and even after that is done, I think I will still have some travelling to do before I can settle anywhere for long.~
@819  = ~You do seem to have a knack for it. I'll probably have to do a bit more travelling myself before I can settle down~
@820  = ~Are you offering your services?~
@821  = ~If I do, I don't think I'll need a cleric, if you know what I mean.~
@822  = ~It isn't really. Just making conversation.~
@823  = ~Well, you might say I have an interest. But you needn't tell me if it makes you uncomfortable.~
@824  = ~Sorry, Gavin. That was more rude than I intended.~
@825  = ~You really are nosy, aren't you?~
@826  = ~That's all right. It isn't as if you would have to decide any time soon.~
@827  = ~That's all right. You have a lot on your mind. Forget I asked, then.~
@828  = ~Ouch. I know you have a lot on your mind, but you don't have to be rude about it.~
@829  = ~So this is Baldur's Gate. It seems subtly different from the last time I was here. People seem more tense. It might just be local trouble, or it might be something more sinister. We should probably be careful.~
@830  = ~You think? We should be careful, but we can't hole up in a comfortable tavern and wait for everyone to get nice and happy again.~
@831  = ~You sound like a mother hen.~
@832  = ~Ho, hum. Seen one city, seen 'em all. Which way to the pub?~
@833  = ~Just think of everything there is to see here!~
@834  = ~No, but I would still try talking to some of the townsfolk, maybe find out why everyone seems edgy.~
@835  = ~And finding a nice, safe base of operations is might be a good idea. Taverns are good for that, because people come and go without a lot of awkward questions.~
@836  = ~Any recommendations?~
@837  = ~If I want your advice, I'll ask for it.~
@838  = ~Maybe later. I want to shop first.~
@839  = ~Let's just do what Scar said first, all right?~
@840  = ~Well, the patrons of the Blushing Mermaid are used to seeing a the unusual, so we would be unlikely to draw much attention, but we'd blend in just as well at the Blade and Stars, I think. The Elfsong is more respectable, but they do get a few exotic travellers, so we would probably not stand out too much. I don't think I've ever been in the Splurging Sturgeon or the Drakon Tavern, so I can't advise, there.~
@841  = ~Unusual is good. Which way to the Blushing Mermaid?~
@842  = ~I'm sure the Blade and Stars will do.~
@843  = ~I've had enough low-lifes for a while. How about the Elfsong?~
@844  = ~Where is the Splurging Sturgeon?~
@845  = ~Where is the Drakon Tavern?~
@846  = ~It doesn't matter, really. We'll just find a place and decide if it suits us then.~
@847  = ~The Blushing Mermaid and the Splurging Sturgeon are both in Northeast Baldur's Gate.~
@848  = ~The Blade and Stars is in Southeast Baldur's Gate.~
@849  = ~The Elfsong is in East Baldur's Gate. Sorcerous Sundries is there, too. You might find that place interesting.~
@850  = ~The Drakon Tavern is in Central Baldur's Gate.~
@851  = ~Good enough.~
@852  = ~No need to get snippy.~
@853  = ~Well there are certainly lots of good places to shop in Baldur's Gate.~
@854  = ~If you wish, but it might not be a bad idea to rest first.~
@855  = ~I'm sure the dangers here are no worse than they are elsewhere, but let's try not to make any enemies, all right?~
@856  = ~Oh, there's plenty to see and do here, all right, but maybe we should look for a base of operations first. Taverns are good for that. People come and go all the time, and no one asks too many questions.~
@857  = ~So, this is where our fate will be decided. Here, in this decrepit temple, we have the chance to finally put an end to this beast once and for all. <CHARNAME>, I have faith in your ability to see us through this, even as I have faith in the ability of light to overcome darkness.~
@858  = ~Lead on! Let the shadows flee before us!~
@859  = ~So, what next?~
@860  = ~The iron shortage. We've got to do something, you know.~
@861  = ~First things first. We'll resupply, investigate local concerns, and get a feel for the current situation.~
@862  = ~How should I know?~
@863  = ~Any suggestions?~
@864  = ~Ask Jaheira. She's always got something to say.~
@865  = ~Yes, we do. What did you have in mind?~
@866  = ~First, we gather information, then we decide on a plan. You should always have the facts first.~
@867  = ~Nothing, yet. I was hoping you'd have something clever to say.~
@868  = ~We need to rest before we do anything else.~
@869  = ~Gavin, give me some peace, please. I'll let you know if I come up with anything.~
@870  = ~That sounds like the best course. I'd like to help, but it does more good to know where it will be most needed.~
@871  = ~You are our leader. The decision will be yours. If you were to ask me, though, I would suggest talking to the people of Nashkel to find out where our help would be most needed.~
@872  = ~Never a bad idea. But what then?~
@873  = ~First, we gather information, then we decide on a plan. I'm too tired to think about it much more, but that would be best.~
@874  = ~That you are giving it some comsideration is enough for me. I would not wait too long to make up your mind, though. The area needs our help.~
@875  = ~Shh! She usually does, but that isn't the point. You are our leader. What do you think we should do?~
@876  = ~So, now what? Nashkel mine's been cleared, and the quality of the iron, and trade, should improve locally, but that isn't going to solve everything.~
@877  = ~You don't give a <PRO_MANWOMAN> a chance for much of a breather, do you?~
@878  = ~Do you expect me to solve all the world's problems?~
@879  = ~I suppose we start chasing bandits. It's like chasing shadows.~
@880  = ~You tell me.~
@881  = ~I don't know what you are going to do, but I am going to look for another cleric.~
@882  = ~Of course we need a break! But once we're rested, we're going to need to decide on a course.~
@883  = ~You can take as long as you like, but that isn't going to improve the lot of the folk around here. I'm not being critical. If you say we need a break, we need a break. But once we're rested, we're going to need to decide on a course.~
@884  = ~You know, I really think you could! Just not all of them today. I was thinking about our immediate concerns.~
@885  = ~Start chasing bandits, unless you have any better ideas.~
@886  = ~A good leader always listens to <PRO_HISHER> advisers. What would you recommend?~
@887  = ~I say we explore the area, get a better feel for where our help would be most useful.~
@888  = ~I'm taking the matter under consideration.~
@889  = ~No, that sounds like the best plan to me.~
@890  = ~I would suggest restocking our supplies and investigating the bandits. They have to come from somewhere.~
@891  = ~Sounds good to me.~
@892  = ~Good enough. If you're open to suggestion, though, I would recommend restocking our supplies and investigating the bandits. They have to come from somewhere.~
@893  = ~Uh, no, not exactly. I was thinking about our immediate concerns.~
@894  = ~It is, but I think it is probably our best course. They have to come from somewhere.~
@895  = ~I wouldn't *tell* you to do anything, my friend, but I might make a recommendation. These bandits have to come from somewhere. I'd start trying to find out where.~
@896  = ~I wouldn't *tell* you to do anything, but I might make a recommendation. These bandits have to come from somewhere. I'd start trying to find out where.~
@897  = ~I am sorry you have not found my services worth retaining, but you are certainly free to make your own decisions. If you would prefer that I leave, I would be happy to do so.~
@898  = ~No, Gavin, just ease up on me a bit.~
@899  = ~That might be for the best. It's time we parted company.~
@900  = ~Very well, I will go along with you for now. But I could be better pleased with our actions. I won't stand for much more of the same, if you know what I mean.~
@901  = ~Very well. I hope you can be made to see the error of your ways before it is too late.~
@902  = ~Every day, we are faced with poverty and violence. It never ends. We've seen raided caravans, the widows of Nashkel, bandits on the roads and worse, orphans everywhere... Even in Beregost, life is unkind for some. I doubt the courtesans outside Feldposts' would have chosen that profession had there been any other choice. Sometimes, I feel powerless to alleviate the misery around me.~
@903  = ~I know what you mean, but we're doing all that we can to help.~
@904  = ~I don't think there's much we can do about it.~
@905  = ~So what do you recommend?~
@906  = ~Actually, I don't think the courtesans mind all that much.~
@907  = ~You can alleviate the misery around me by not talking about it so much.~
@908  = ~I suppose you are right. We are doing what we can. Doesn't it bother you, though?~
@909  = ~Of course, Gavin. I'm not blind. I just keep hoping that once this part of the world is a little safer, trade will improve, and everyone will be able to live a little better.~
@910  = ~Not really. I know we're doing all we can, and I must be content with that. There are a lot of evils you can't fix by praying and smiting any evil you can find, Gavin.~
@911  = ~And that, my friend, is why you are leading this group. You have the vision to see past the skirmishes and filth and hold on to the thought of a better future.~
@912  = ~I know that. And I know we're doing the best we can. The knowledge doesn't keep me from wishing I could see past the skirmishes and filth to a better future, though.~
@913  = ~I think we could. I believe there has to be more we can do to help the people we meet every day, even if it's only in a small way. Doesn't the poverty and oppression bother you, though?~
@914  = ~And that, my friend, is why you are leading this group. Even if we haven't done as much as we could have yet, you have the vision to see past the skirmishes and filth and hold on to the thought of a better future.~
@915  = ~Forgive me for disagreeing with you, but I must. There *is* more we can do. The knowledge doesn't keep me from wishing I could see past the skirmishes and filth to a better future, though.~
@916  = ~There is always something more we can do, but I must admit we are doing well. Doesn't the affliction of the people bother you, though?~
@917  = ~I think there has to be more we can do to help the people we meet every day, even if it's only in a small way. Doesn't the poverty and oppression bother you, though?~
@918  = ~I believe there has to be more we can do to help the people we meet every day, even if it's only in a small way. Fighting bandits and... monsters... is a start, but hardly the ultimate solution. Doesn't the poverty and oppression bother you?~
@919  = ~How can you even think that? If you were a woman, would you choose to let every filthy mongrel with enough coin to buy your time violate you like that? It's degrading, and worse. Set a price on your body, and pretty soon, you'd start to think even your life isn't worth much more.~
@920  = ~It's a symptom of the evil that infects this world, but not the disease. I believe there has to be more we can do to help the people we meet every day, even if it's only in a small way. Fighting bandits and... monsters... is a start, but hardly the ultimate solution. Doesn't the poverty and oppression bother you?~
@921  = ~How can you even think that? Would you choose to let every filthy mongrel with enough coin to buy your time violate you like that? It's degrading, and worse. Set a price on your body, and pretty soon, you'd start to think even your life isn't worth much more.~
@922  = ~I suppose I do preach a bit more than I should. Still, I believe there has to be more we can do to help the people we meet every day, even if it's only in a small way. Fighting bandits and... monsters... is a start, but hardly the ultimate solution. Doesn't the poverty and oppression bother you?~
@923  = ~Fine! I'll save you from the sermon, since you're in such a foul mood.~
@924  = ~I know we still have a long way to go, but I can't help feeling happier that the bastard is dead.~
@925  = ~It isn't like you to be so vengeful, Gavin.~
@926  = ~What a horrible thing to say!~
@927  = ~I know what you mean. Personally, I would have liked to see him suffer more.~
@928  = ~I'm just glad it's over.~
@929  = ~I'm getting pretty tired of the suffering and ruined lives these vermin leave in their wake. It has to end, and if my hands get a little dirty in the process, so be it.~
@930  = ~You're changing, Gavin. The cleric we met outside the Song of the Morning would not have said that.~
@931  = ~I could not agree more.~
@932  = ~Just don't become a monster to destroy one.~
@933  = ~Whatever gets the job done.~
@934  = ~That might have been satisfying, but it would not have served any additional purpose. His death was enough. I'm getting pretty tired of the suffering and ruined lives these vermin leave in their wake. It has to end, and if my hands get a little dirty in the process, so be it.~
@935  = ~It isn't over. We've made a start, but it is far from over. I'm getting pretty tired of the suffering and ruined lives these vermin leave in their wake. It has to end, and if my hands get a little dirty in the process, so be it.~
@936  = ~Maybe not, but I've seen some things that man never expected to see. Somebody has to stand up for that which is right and decent in this world, or it will surely perish. I'm glad we stand together.~
@937  = ~Somebody has to stand up for that which is right and decent in this world, or it will surely perish. I'm glad we stand together.~
@938  = ~Wise words, <CHARNAME>. But, no, I'm stronger than that. Somebody has to stand up for that which is right and decent in this world, or it will surely perish. I'm glad we stand together.~
@939  = ~As long as the good is served. Somebody has to stand up for that which is right and decent in this world, or it will surely perish. I'm glad we stand together.~
@940  = ~I'm sorry for picking such a bad time to bring this up, but we're getting to the point where I might have to make some... arrangements.~
@941  = ~Do you mean about your daughter?~
@942  = ~What are you talking about?~
@943  = ~We've made an enemy of the entire Iron Throne, and you're telling me that you've got to make arrangements *now*?~
@944  = ~You had better not be running from the law.~
@945  = ~Yes, I mean my daughter. She means everything to me. What we are doing is dangerous. I know that. If I die, and you survive, would you do something for me?~
@946  = ~What would you like me to do?~
@947  = ~I'm not making any promises. If you want to make any arrangements, you're going to have to live to see them through.~
@948  = ~You're on your own, Gavin. I'm not doing anything for you.~
@949  = ~I'm talking about Lanie, my daughter.~
@950  = ~Lanie means everything to me. What we are doing is dangerous. I know that. If I die, and you survive, would you do something for me?~
@951  = ~We're running out of time, and our danger is very real. I've got to make some plans... just in case.~
@952  = ~This might come as a surprise to you, but I have a daughter. She is five years old, and her name is Lanie. It's a long story, and I don't really want to go into any details, but Lanie's mother and I are estranged, and have been since her birth.~
@953  = ~I'm not running from anything, anymore. But we're running out of time, so I have to make some arrangements... just in case.~
@954  = ~*grips your shoulder* Thank you, my friend.~
@955  = ~I want you to take a message to both Lanie and to Miranda, her mother.~
@956  = ~I want you to tell Lanie that I love her, and that I'm very proud of her. Tell her that I did not want to leave her, but I was doing something I believed in. If you can get it off my hand, give her my ring. But the most important thing is that she knows that I love her very, very much.~
@957  = ~I'd like you to remind Miranda of our agreement that my brother Gordon would stand as Lanie's godfather, if anything happened to me. She agreed to this years ago, but I'm not sure she remembers. Gordon is older than me, but his youngest is even younger than Lanie. He is a fine man, and a good father. If Miranda needs any help, as far as Lanie is concerned, she can count on Gordon and his wife, Emma, whenever she needs it.~
@958  = ~There is also the matter of Lanie's education. She is supposed to be enrolled at the temple of Oghma in Baldur's Gate. Her education is going to cost over a thousand gold pieces. That's why I took up adventuring in the first place.~
@959  = ~Miranda and Lanie live in Beregost, not far from the Tavenhurst Manor, in a house that shares a back garden with Roe and Mirianne's house. It's on the same street as the Red Sheaf Inn, but on the opposite side, and all the way at the end.~
@960  = ~Would you pass along those two messages, and see that Miranda gets my share of the treasure, for Lanie's education?~
@961  = ~Of course.~
@962  = ~I'll try.~
@963  = ~I think if you're going to die, I'm not going to be far behind you.~
@964  = ~We'll see how this ends. You aren't dead yet.~
@965  = ~I'd like you to remind Miranda of our agreement that my brother Gordon would stand as Lanie's godfather, if anything happened to me. She agreed to this years ago, but I'm not sure she remembers. Gordon is older than me, but his youngest is even younger than Lanie. He is a fine man, and a good father. If Miranda needs any help, as far as Lanie is concerned, she can count on Gordon and his wife, Emma, whenever she needs it.~
@966  = ~Well hear me out, anyway. I want you to take a message to both Lanie and to Miranda, her mother.~
@967  = ~I thought you my friend. Oh, well. Let's hope I don't die.~
@968  = ~Thank you, my friend.~
@969  = ~I could ask no more.~
@970  = ~*smile* I think you are destined for more than a shallow grave.~
@971  = ~*chuckles* No, I'm not, and I hope to keep it that way. Well, my friend, I won't pressure you for a commitment, but I hope that you will honor a father's last wish for his child.~
@972  = ~Be careful, my friend. These catacombs are unwholesome. Believe nothing you see.~
@973  = ~Aren't you a right little ray of sunshine?~
@974  = ~Oh, I'm wary all right.~
@975  = ~What is there to be afraid of among the silent dead?~
@976  = ~When I was young, not long after I went to the Song of the Morning Temple, I went exploring. I found a key that let me into the catacombs beneath the temple. I unlocked the grille, went through, and it closed and locked behind me. I was startled by a spider, and I dropped the key. I fumbled to catch it on the way down, and managed to kick it back through the grille into the vestibule. Most of the first day I was locked in there, I explored the crypts. It was two days before old Bram found me there. As punishment for my disobedience, I was assigned to help Bram with the next lot of housekeeping: cleaning out all the rat droppings and dead flowers, that sort of thing. We came across a clutch of undead one door further along than I had gone in my solitary exploration.~
@977  = ~All I ask is that you be careful. Not everything is as it seems.~
@978  = ~With good reason. When I was young, not long after I went to the Song of the Morning Temple, I went exploring. I found a key that let me into the catacombs beneath the temple. I unlocked the grille, went through, and it closed and locked behind me. I was startled by a spider, and I dropped the key. I fumbled to catch it on the way down, and managed to kick it back through the grille into the vestibule. Most of the first day I was locked in there, I explored the crypts. It was two days before old Bram found me there. As punishment for my disobedience, I was assigned to help Bram with the next lot of housekeeping: cleaning out all the rat droppings and dead flowers, that sort of thing. We came across a clutch of undead one door further along than I had gone in my solitary exploration.~
@979  = ~Good. When I was young, not long after I went to the Song of the Morning Temple, I went exploring. I found a key that let me into the catacombs beneath the temple. I unlocked the grille, went through, and it closed and locked behind me. I was startled by a spider, and I dropped the key. I fumbled to catch it on the way down, and managed to kick it back through the grille into the vestibule. Most of the first day I was locked in there, I explored the crypts. It was two days before old Bram found me there. As punishment for my disobedience, I was assigned to help Bram with the next lot of housekeeping: cleaning out all the rat droppings and dead flowers, that sort of thing. We came across a clutch of undead one door further along than I had gone in my solitary exploration.~
@980  = ~Enough. When I was young, not long after I went to the Song of the Morning Temple, I went exploring. I found a key that let me into the catacombs beneath the temple. I unlocked the grille, went through, and it closed and locked behind me. I was startled by a spider, and I dropped the key. I fumbled to catch it on the way down, and managed to kick it back through the grille into the vestibule. Most of the first day I was locked in there, I explored the crypts. It was two days before old Bram found me there. As punishment for my disobedience, I was assigned to help Bram with the next lot of housekeeping: cleaning out all the rat droppings and dead flowers, that sort of thing. We came across a clutch of undead one door further along than I had gone in my solitary exploration.~
@981  = ~When this is over, I will need to leave your company for a time. Once the present crisis is resolved, Baldur's Gate will be more peaceful. I must go back to Beregost and get Lanie. I will bring her back here, to Baldur's Gate, so I can get her enrolled in school. She will not be at liberty to return home for several months, so I will be able to bear you company a while, after that. If you're still in Baldur's Gate, I'll rejoin you.~
@982  = ~Anyway, on we go.~
@983  = ~You first!~
@984  = ~Indeed, yet <PRO_HESHE> has chosen the way of pain.~
@985  = ~Indeed! Though I would be most grateful if you would speak of this to no one.~
@986  = ~What was that? Oh, never mind. I probably do not want to know.~
@987  = ~If you can retrieve the emeralds, I am content.~
@988  = ~You have earned your reward, bringing a murderer to justice.~
@989  = ~As mayor, I thank you.~
@990  = ~Very true.~
@991  = ~Madness, indeed, to take from one who has nothing!~
@992  = ~Thank you.~
@993  = ~See you soon! Bye!~
@994  = ~Oh hush. Of course <PRO_HESHE> knows what <PRO_HESHE>'s doing.~
@995  = ~<CHARNAME> makes the decisions around here, Gavin.~
@996  = ~*sigh* Never mind.~
@997  = ~Farewell.~
@998  = ~*sigh* Just end it.~
@999  = ~Thank you.~
@1000  = ~Wisdom or folly, it matters not. Alas, that my masterpiece should go unfinished!~
@1001  = ~Alas, Ellesime!~
@1002  = ~I must go elsewhere for help.~
@1003  = ~Thank you, though there is nothing you could have done to prevent this.~
@1004  = ~Adorable! Bye, now!~
@1005  = ~Watch, now!~
@1006  = ~Even so!~
@1007  = ~No, no. We'll all be family, you'll see.~
@1008  = ~Yes! Now hold still!~
@1009  = ~Yes, now hurry!~
@1010  = ~I think it shall not be so easy!~
@1011  = ~Still, I have my life. Farewell.~
@1012  = ~Hush... Now, Oompah...~
@1013  = ~That's enough, <CHARNAME>! You've had your fun, now leave these young people to their follies.~
@1014  = ~Miss, please, calm down! No one is going to hurt you! We're going to leave now, and you two can get on with whatever we interrupted. Isn't that right, <CHARNAME>?~
@1015  = ~Er... yes, of course. We'll leave you alone now.~
@1016  = ~I don't know about that, Gavin. She looks like she's got some spirit, if you know what I mean.~
@1017  = ~We're very sorry for upsetting you, miss. It was just <CHARNAME>'s idea of a joke.~
@1018  = ~Please excuse us, and we'll be on our way.~
@1019  = ~I am not going to help you slaughter an innocent boy!~
@1020  = ~If that's what you want to do, you have to go through me first!~
@1021  = ~Aiiiiiyia! Gods, <CHARNAME>, I can face anything on Faerun, but not spiders. Too damn many legs...~
@1022  = ~Gods, <CHARNAME>, you're a bastard, and no mistake! Couldn't you have just left these young people to their follies? I'll back you because I have to, but you're no friend of mine.~
@1023  = ~Eek!~